<paragraph blockId="10.[188,1400,720,922]" pageId="10" pageNumber="31">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Banks" baseAuthorityYear="1920" box="[189,432,720,746]" class="Insecta" family="Sialidae" genus="Ilyobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Megaloptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bimaculatus">
<emphasis box="[189,432,720,746]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="31">Ilyobius bimaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known solely from the female 
<typeStatus box="[816,922,720,746]" pageId="10" pageNumber="31">holotype</typeStatus>
, which is in poor condition (
<figureCitation box="[1249,1318,720,747]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="13.[188,231,1998,2024]" captionTargetBox="[189,1386,1200,1937]" captionTargetId="figure-347@13.[189,1398,1173,1960]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Fig. 8. Holotype female of Ilyobius bimaculatus (Banks, 1920), dorsal habitus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5761453" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5761453/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="31">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
). Only few diagnostic characters were observed, which include an area just behind the antennal sockets with a semicircular brown spot. The dorsal area adjacent to the compound eyes has a brown spot, posteriorly extended, flame-shaped, with three-pronged posterior extensions. The gonocoxites 8 appear as small, paired, ovoid sclerites in lateral and ventral view. The gonapophyses 8 are observed as lateral smooth, glabrous, ovoid plates in lateral and ventral view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
